Since the periodic payment is quarterly, if we consider the annual percentage rate of 10.57% to determine the present value, we must divide the APR by four since the computation is quarterly. As a result, we'll use the following equation to express the rate in our calculations:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &=\dfrac{0.1057}{4}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the present value of the annuity with a constant growth rate of 2%.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{PV of Growing Annuity} &=\$150,000\times\dfrac{1-\left(\dfrac{1+0.02}{1+\dfrac{0.1057}{4}}\right)^t}{\dfrac{0.1057}{4}}
\\[20pt]
 &=\$150,000\times\dfrac{1-\left(\dfrac{1.02}{1.026425}\right)^{25}}{0.006425}
\\[10pt]
 &=\$150,000\times\dfrac{0.145280}{0.006425}
\\[10pt]
 &=\$150,000\times22.6117
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$3,391,755.83}
\end{aligned}$$

The present value of the periodic payment, according to our calculations, is $3,391,755.83.

We'll use the following formula to combine the initial payment and the annuity's present value:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Offer's Value} &= \text{PV of Growing Annuity}+\text{Initial Downpayment}
\end{aligned}$$
